quot;NWN, same bunk. The game should have been way bigger then it was, and I mean way bigger. Atari forced Bioware to release it unfinished because they were in financial need, and it was some fast cash for their bank account. NWN isn't what it should be and probably never will be, because it upset too many people the way it was released so poorly. It should and could have been a much bigger and badder thing and made ALOT more profit for them as well IF Atari had let Bioware go and finish it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Huh?  Unfinished?  WTF are you talking about?<br>
<br>
NWN met it's intial design objectives, and it met them very well.  Are you basing your assessment on the scenario/campaign that came with the release of NWN?  Have you used the Toolset extensively?  Have you played many single and multiplayer modules created and released by the user base?  Have you played on any of the 50 or so persistent worlds out there right now?  Have you delved into the custom programming, scripting, and graphic models that have been developed by the user base?<br>
<br>
There is a MASSIVE community pushing the frontiers of NWN beyond what anyone thought it would be.  <br>
<br>
The only problem with NWN is that it requires a bit of &quot;work&quot; for the average user to find the quality material that has been produced for it - which doesn't appeal to the lazy nature of your average gamer.<br>
<br>
I've been playing on NWN persistent worlds and have been designing with the Toolset for many months now and I'm quite happy with what Bioware developed.  Furthermore, Bioware is continuing to support the product with patches, updates, reskins, development support (in the form of code and essay style advice) as well as publishing expansion packs (one due out very soon and an epic level expansion in the works).<br>
<br>
The Toolset itself is a work of art in terms of ease of use and its comprehensive nature.  Try using any other editor out there and you'll soon find out what I mean. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=banegrivm>Banegrivm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 575<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/8/03 2:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1562.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: IMHO, the D&amp;D ruleset ..</span><hr size=1> NWN was never completed when it was released. Bioware was still working on the project, hence why all the spells weren't in, and why the creature database was so sparse. Atari forced Bioware to release NWN unfinished because they wanted to see a return on their investment, due to their difficult fiscal problems.<br>
<br>
The rest of NWN is to be released in various patches, and expansion packs as they finish the work for it. The toolset for example was supposed to be completely point and click where you needed to know no scripting at all, just as an example of how it is unfinished, let alone alot of the missing content such as the aforementioned creature database, and item listing.<br>
<br>
