Sovereign Lord of the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.1stfistoflight.com" target="top">1st Fist of Light</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sevlin>Sevlin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/8/03 11:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1562.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: IMHO, the D&amp;D ruleset ..</span><hr size=1> The idea sounds interesting, but from what I've seen of most D&amp;D -- even AD&amp;D -- computer games (most especially NWN) is that you level up very quickly, and become immensely powerful while the monsters remain lacking, as Bjond mentioned.  What makes me wonder most about an online D&amp;D world is the lack of pausing.  In NWN and other computer D&amp;D titles, you at least had the ability to pause the game, hash some ideas out with your groupmates, talk it over, and then implement some sort of plan of attack before the game resumed.  The fact that you would be unable to do this in an online environment (I should think, anyway) means you'll lose that element of teamwork and cooperation that has, for me, made tabletop games such rewarding experiences.<br>
<br>
As for NWN, it was released too early, but I'd hardly say it ruined the game.  The game was in development for well over two years, and I can't recall a single time they said no scripting would be required.  You CAN make an adventure without scripting, but it's going to be boring.  Knowledge in C+ was always going to be required for custom scripts and modules.  I think the only thing NWN lacked upon release was a large enough variety of tilesets.  But as others have mentioned, the NWN community has more than made up for what BioWare was unable to provide right away.  Even now, before the expansion, one can find plenty of custom made monsters, tilesets, scripts, objects, etc, that the community has made.  A community-run game with community-created add-ons and features was ALWAYS what they wanted NWN to be, and it is.<br>
<br>
For me, NWN was and is a great game to play with your friends.  Like other D&amp;D games, if you play single player, it'll probably be disappointing.  With the pause and command feature, and a DM available, it can be just like a tabletop experience, so long as everyone communicates.<br>
<br>
As for D&amp;D Online?  It just wouldn't be D&amp;D without a DM.<br>
<br>
Gerbo's mun. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sevlin>Sevlin</A> at: 6/8/03 2:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kurley>Kurley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 799<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/8/03 2:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1562.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: IMHO, the D&amp;D ruleset ..</span><hr size=1> &quot;NWN was never completed when it was released. Bioware was still working on the project, hence why all the spells weren't in, and why the creature database was so sparse. Atari forced Bioware to release NWN unfinished because they wanted to see a return on their investment, due to their difficult fiscal problems.<br>
<br>
The rest of NWN is to be released in various patches, and expansion packs as they finish the work for it. The toolset for example was supposed to be completely point and click where you needed to know no scripting at all, just as an example of how it is unfinished, let alone alot of the missing content such as the aforementioned creature database, and item listing.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bane...what the hell are you talking about and where are you pulling this information from?<br>
<br>
If you spent any time reading the design documents during the development of the game, Bioware was very specific on the number of monsters, the number of spells, the layout of the entire toolset, the fact that scripting would be POSSIBLE (read, the ability to script is a bonus feature, not a shortcoming as it allows nearly infinite flexibility), the number of the tilesets etc...etc...etc...and the out of the box NWN everyone bought was bang on with the design document.<br>
<br>
NOWHERE did it state that the Toolset would be &quot;point and click&quot; only.  Noone wants that anyways.  There is no way any programmer or group of programmers could anticipate all of the scripts that the users would want so they a) created a scripting language specifically for NWN so that people could do what they wanted, b) actually held and published classes and lessons on how to script and c) have and continue to release many scripts on a weekly basis.<br>
<br>
I've been using NWN since beta and I've gone through virtually every design element there is, and the Toolset if just flat out wonderful.  Try designing something with Dungeon Siege or Morowind before you bitch out NWN.<br>
<br>
Some spells in the PHB just don't translate to computer gaming.  Similarly, it is unrealistic to design every single monster in the D&amp;D universe, so Bioware presented a &quot;core&quot; or critters, and most importantly, gave the users the ability to customize all the statistical (stats, abilities, scripts, classes etc...) data than your heart desires.  Moreover, they showed the community how to reskin and even remodel anything in the game.  The same goes for items.<br>
<br>
However here is the most important and most valuable feature of NWN:  the community.  I've been working on a World of Greyhawk persistent world module for some time and I often find myself saying &quot;Damn, I really need [insert thing here].&quot;<br>
<br>
So what do I do?  There is a request forum on NWVault.  I needed a decent model for Orcus, Demonprince of the Undead.  I put up a request and about a week later, presto, some dude out there designed one while another dude designed the Wand of Orcus (with three different variants and particle effects).  Find me any game that has a community willing to do that.<br>
<br>
Don't believe me yet?  Here, check out this and see what these fellows are whipping up with &quot;shitty&quot; NWN product:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.city-of-doors.com/">www.city-of-doors.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Check out the custom models they've designed, and the character race/class generator, and the custom tilesets...<br>
